om.au/talent/cricket/chris-hartley.html |archivedate=2008-07-19 }} Pivot Sport Profile for Chris Hartley</ref>\n*[[Craig Philipson]] &ndash; Queensland Bulls<ref name=\"btw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qldcricket.com.au/images/Between%20the%20Wickets/btwFebruary2005.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022212953/http://www.qldcricket.com.au/images/Between%20the%20Wickets/btwFebruary2005.pdf |archivedate=2009-10-22 }} Between the Wickets (page 19)</ref>\n\n===Rugby league===\n*[[Dane Gagai]] &ndash; Brisbane Broncos and Newcastle Knights<ref name=\"dgagai\">http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/rugby-league/brisbane-broncos/broncos-gagai-in-new-twoyear-nrl-deal-20120319-1vfll.html</ref>\n\n===Rugby union===\n*[[Tom Banks (rugby player born 1994)|Tom Banks]] - Queensland Reds, ACT Brumbies, Wallabies\n*[[Angus Cottrell]] &ndash; Melbourne Rebels flanker\n*[[Hugh Alexander Dunn|Hugh Dunn]] - Uncapped Queensland, Rugby Half Blue and Blue - University of Queensland, Australian Universities\n*[[Will Genia]] &ndash; Queensland Reds and the Wallabies (Vice Captain); now plays for Melbourne Rebels\n*[[Roger Gould (rugby)|Roger Gould]] &ndash; Queensland Reds and the Wallabies<ref name=\"rgould\">http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/union/bbc-hardman-wont-back-down/2008/07/31/1217097474396.html BBC hardman won't back down</ref>\n*[[James Horwill]] &ndash; Queensland Reds and the Wallabies; former Qld Reds and Australian Wallabies Captain; Harlequins<ref name=\"jhorwill\">http://qru.com.au/reds/reds.rugby/page/40234/section/40810 QRU Profile for James Horwill</ref><ref name=\"soc-jhorwill\">{{Cite news| title = James Horwill|newspaper = Sons of the College|location = Brisbane, Australia|pages = 6|publisher=Brisbane Boys' College|date = October 2009}}</ref>\n*[[John Roe (rugby union)|John Roe]] &ndash; Queensland Reds and the Wallabies; former Qld Reds Captain<ref name=\"jroe\">http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/sport/roe-shoulders-retirement/2008/07/31/1217097370240.html Brisbane Times Article - Roe shoulders retirement</ref>\n\n===Football===\n*[[Zachary Anderson]] &ndash; Central Coast Mariners<ref>(in English (Australia)) {{cite web |url=http://au.linkedin.com/pub/zac-anderson/75/9a3/43a |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131104182401/http://au.linkedin.com/pub/zac-anderson/75/9a3/43a |archivedate=2013-11-04 }}</ref>\n*[[Ross Archibald]] &ndash; Melbourne Heart<ref>(in English (Australia)) https://sslcam.news.com.au/cam/authorise?url=http%3a%2f%2fwww.adelaidenow.com.au%2fsport%2ffootball%2fmelbourne-heart-throw-18-year-old-ross-archibald-a-lifeline%2fstory-fnddhv0x-1226590241897&channel=pc</ref>\n*[[Michael Zullo]] &ndash; FC Utrecht<ref>(in English (Australia)) Portal 2002. Brisbane, Queensland, Australia: Brisbane Boys' College. 2002. pp. 31</ref>\n\n===Swimming===\n*[[Kieren Perkins]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|OAM}} &ndash; Olympic gold medallist<ref name=\"kperkins\">http://www.csnz.co.nz/default,5474,kieren_perkins.sm;jsessionid=9BE8B80094A69BB5E1725AAB8E91F04D CSNZ Speaker Profile for Kieren Perkins</ref>\n\n===Track & field===\n*[[Mitchell Watt]]{{spaced endash}} long jumper, silver medalist, London Summer Olympics 2012\n\n*[[Ash Moloney]] Decathlon Gold medalist, U20 World Champion 2018 Tempere, Finland\n\n==See also==\n*[[Old boy network]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brisbane Boy's College Old Boys}}\n[[Category:Lists of Australian men]]\n[[Category:Lists of people educated in Queensland by school affiliation]]\n[[Category:Brisbane-related lists|Brisbane Boys]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n<!-- Please don't add anyone to this list without a reliable reference to back up both their notability as well as their status as BBC alumni. If no reference is supplied, the alumni listing can be challenged/removed at any time. Thanks. -->\nThis is a list of notable alumni who attended [[Brisbane Boys' College]]. [[Alumnus|Alumni]] of Brisbane Boys' College are known as Old Collegians and may elect to join the school's [[alumni association]], the BBC Old Collegians' Association.<ref name=BBCOCA>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.qld.edu.au/community/collegians/default.htm |title=Old Collegians' Association |accessdate=2007-12-05 |work=College Community |publisher=Brisbane Boys' College |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110145021/http://www.bbc.qld.edu.au/community/collegians/default.htm |archivedate=2007-11-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<!-- Please do not add alumni without providing a valid, third-party source -->\n<!-- Please add alumni in alphabetical order under appropriate category -->\n\n==Academic==\n*[[George G. Watson]] - Cambridge don\n\n==Business==\n*[[David Lenigas]] &ndash; [[Chief Executive Officer]] of Lonrho Africa Limited<ref name=\"DALenigas\">{{cite encyclopedia| editor = Suzannah Pearce| encyclopedia = Who's Who in Business Live!| title = LENIGAS David Anthony| date = 2006-11-17| publisher = Crown Content Pty Ltd| location = North Melbourne, Vic}}</ref>\n\n==Defence==\n*[[Galfry Gatacre]] {{postnominal|CBE|DSC|DSO}} (1907\u20131983), Royal Australian Navy rear admiral and first-class cricketer\n*Squadron Leader [[Beaufort Mosman Hunter Palmer]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|DFC*}} \u2013 pilot, war hero, farmer<ref name=\"ConciseHistory\">{{cite book\n | author    = <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n | others    = RAAF Historical Section\n | year      = 1995\n | title     = Units of the Royal Australian Air Force: A Concise History. Volume 2: Fighter Units\n | location  = Canberra\n | publisher = Australian Government Publishing Service\n | isbn      = 0-644-42794-9\n | page      = 18\n | url       = http://airpower.airforce.gov.au/admin/productfiles/publication/materials/545/volume%202%20-%20fighter%20units_web.pdf\n | quote     = In the period 3\u201310 May, unit aircraft combined with others in attacks on enemy positions in support of the Army advance and capture of Wewak. The Commanding Officer, Squadron Leader B.M. Palmer, was injured on 29 May 1945 when he trod on an old American anti-personnel mine.\n | accessdate= 16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Australia_In_The_War\">{{cite book\n | last       = Long\n | first      = Gavin Merrick\n | date       = 1963\n | title      = Australia in the War of 1939-1945: Series One, Army, Volume VII The Final Campaigns\n | url        = https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MYoGAQAAIAAJ\n | archive-url= https://www.awm.gov.au/images/collection/pdf/RCDIG1070075--1-.pdf\n | archive-date=1963\n | location   = Adelaide\n | publisher  = The Griffin Press\n | page       = 156\n | isbn       = 0642993661\n | access-date= 17 August 2016\n | quote      = A fortnight earlier a few Japanese tanks had been located. A New Zealand Corsair pilot reported having seen enemy tanks at Rurl Bay in the north-east of the Island. Squadron Leader B.M.H. Palmer, commanding No 5 Squadron RAAF led other Corsairs to the target and guided them while they attacked three tanks, all of which they damaged. As a result of this and a later attack two were destroyed but the third was evidently moved away.}}</ref>\n\n==Media and arts==\n* [[Charles Cottier]] \u2013 [[actor]]<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3937907/ IMDB page for Charles Cottier]</ref>\n* [[Rex Cramphorn]] \u2013 theatre director, costume designer, critic and translator<ref>[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cramphorn-rex-roy-15453 Cramphorn, Rex Roy (1941\u20131991) ADB]</ref>\n* [[Lachlan Gillespie]] \u2013 member of [[The Wiggles]]<ref>[http://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/logan/join-the-wiggles-dorothy-the-dinosaur-wags-the-dog-and-captain-feathersword-for-their-taking-off-tour/story-fn8m0u8i-1226629966526 Join The Wiggles, Dorothy the Dinosaur, Wags the Dog and Captain Feathersword for their 'Taking Off' tour]</ref>\n* [[Darren Middleton]] - [[musician]] - former member of [[Powderfinger]]\n\n==Medicine and health sciences==\n* [[Franklin White]] \u2013  President of Canadian Public Health Association (1986\u201388); Medal of Honor (1997) [[Pan-American Health Organization]]; endowed chair at [[Dalhousie University]] (1982\u201389) and [[Aga Khan University]] 1998\u20132003\n\n==Rhodes Scholars==\n*[[Hugh Dunn]] (1949)<ref name=Rhodes/>\n*[[John Wylie (businessman)|John Wylie]] (1983)<ref name=Rhodes>{{cite web |url=http://www.uq.edu.au/about/docs/rhodes-scholars-list.doc |title=Queensland Rhodes Scholars |accessdate=2008-02-07 |format=doc |work=Rhodes Scholarship |publisher=University of Queensland}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\n===Australian rules football===\n*[[Clint Bizzell]] &ndash; Geelong Football Club and Melbourne Demons<ref name=\"afl\"/>\n*[[Courtenay Dempsey]] &ndash; Essendon Bombers<ref name=\"afl\"/>\n*[[Chris Scott (Australian footballer)|Chris Scott]] &ndash; Brisbane Lions<ref name=\"afl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.qld.edu.au/activities/afl/default.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905133918/http://www.bbc.qld.edu.au/activities/afl/default.htm |archivedate=2008-09-05 }} BBC AFL page</ref>\n*[[Hamish Simpson]] &ndash; Geelong Cats<ref name=\"afl\"/>\n\n===Cricket===\n*[[Chris Hartley]] &ndash; Queensland Bulls<ref name=\"chartley\">{{cite web |url=http://pivotsport.com.au/talent/cricket/chris-hartley.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719120936/http://pivotsport.com.au/talent/cricket/chris-hartley.html |archivedate=2008-07-19 }} Pivot Sport Profile for Chris Hartley</ref>\n*[[Craig Philipson]] &ndash; Queensland Bulls<ref name=\"btw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qldcricket.com.au/images/Between%20the%20Wickets/btwFebruary2005.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/